Alice is correct. Under normal atmospheric pressure, water’s freezing point is 0 °C. At temperatures below 0 °C (e.g., –10 °C) water is already solid ice; it doesn’t “freeze” at –10 °C because the phase change has already occurred. Bob’s statement that water freezes at –10 °C is therefore inaccurate. [end of text]


